'''Microsporidiosis''' is an opportunistic intestinal infection that causes [[diarrhea]] and wasting in [[immunocompromised]] individuals ([[HIV]], for example). It results from different species of [[microsporidia]], a group of microbial (unicellular) fungi.<ref name="urlMicrosporidiosis: Parasitic Infections: Merck Manual Home Health Handbook">{{cite web |url=http://www.merckmanuals.com/home/infections/parasitic_infections/microsporidiosis.html |title=Microsporidiosis: Parasitic Infections: Merck Manual Home Health Handbook |work= |accessdate=}}</ref>

In [[HIV]] infected individuals, microsporidiosis generally occurs when [[CD4]]+ [[T cell]] counts fall below 100.

==Classification==
Although it is classified as a [[protozoal disease]] in [[ICD-10]], their phylogenetic placement has been resolved to be within the [[Fungi]]; however, they are highly divergent and rapidly evolving.<ref name="pmid15777637">{{cite journal |author=Didier ES |title=Microsporidiosis: an emerging and opportunistic infection in humans and animals |journal=Acta Trop. |volume=94 |issue=1 |pages=61–76 |year=2005 |month=April |pmid=15777637 |doi=10.1016/j.actatropica.2005.01.010 |url=http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0001-706X(05)00029-X}}</ref><ref name="pmid10666703">{{cite journal |author=Keeling PJ, Luker MA, Palmer JD |title=Evidence from beta-tubulin phylogeny that microsporidia evolved from within the fungi |journal=Mol. Biol. Evol. |volume=17 |issue=1 |pages=23–31 |year=2000 |month=January |pmid=10666703 |doi= |url=http://mbe.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=10666703}}</ref><ref name="pmcidPMC2742732">{{cite journal |author=Keeling PJ |last2=Madhani |first2=Hiten D. |title=Five Questions about Microsporidia |journal=PloS Pathogens |volume=5 |issue=9 |pages=e1000489 |year=2009 |month=September |pmid=19779558 |pmc=2742732 |doi=10.1371/journal.ppat.1000489 |url=http://www.plospathogens.org/article/info:doi/10.1371/journal.ppat.1000489 |editor1-last=Madhani |editor1-first=Hiten D.}}</ref> As unicellular eukaryotes they are still generally considered to be [[Protists]], and some sources classify microsporidiosis as a [[mycosis]].<ref>{{MeshName|Microsporidiosis}}</ref>

==Causative agents==
At least 14 microsporidian species have been recognized as human [[pathogen]]s, spread across eight genera:
* ''[[Brachiola]]''
** ''B. algerae'', ''B. connori'', ''B. vesicularum''
* ''[[Encephalitozoon]]''
** ''E. cuniculi'', ''E. hellem'', ''E. intestinalis''
* Enterocytozoon
** ''E. bieneusi''
* ''[[Microsporidium]]''
** ''M. ceylonensis'', ''M. africanum''
* ''[[Nosema]]''
** ''N. ocularum''
* ''[[Pleistophora]]  sp.''
* ''[[Trachipleistophora]]''
** ''T. hominis'', ''T. anthropophthera''
* ''[[Vittaforma]]''
** ''V. corneae.''

The primary causes are ''[[Enterocytozoon bieneusi]]'' and ''[[Encephalitozoon intestinalis]]''.<ref name="pmid18803616">{{cite journal |author=Lanternier F, Boutboul D, Menotti J, ''et al.'' |title=Microsporidiosis in solid organ transplant recipients: two Enterocytozoon bieneusi cases and review |journal=Transpl Infect Dis |volume=11 |issue=1 |pages=83–8 |year=2009 |month=February |pmid=18803616 |doi=10.1111/j.1399-3062.2008.00347.x}}</ref>

==Life cycle==
[[Image:Microsporidiosis 01.png|thumb|right|Life cycle of the various organisms that cause microsporidiosis.]]

''(Coded to [[:Image:Microsporidiosis 01.png|image]] at right).''
# The infective form of microsporidia is the resistant [[spore]] and it can survive for an exteneded period of time in the environment.
# The spore extrudes its polar tubule and infects the host cell.
# The spore injects the infective [[sporoplasm]] into the [[eukaryotic]] host cell through the polar tubule.
# Inside the cell, the sporoplasm undergoes extensive multiplication either by [[Protozoal merogony|merogony]] (binary fission) or [[schizogony]] (multiple fission).
# This development can occur either in direct contact with the host cell [[cytoplasm]] (''[[Encephalitozoon bieneusi|E. bieneusi]]'') or inside a [[vacuole]] called a [[parasitophorous]] vacuole (''[[Encephalitozoon intestinalis|E. intestinalis]]''). Either free in the cytoplasm or inside a parasitophorous vacuole, microsporidia develop by [[sporogony]] to mature spores.
# During sporogony, a thick wall is formed around the spore, which provides resistance to adverse environmental conditions. When the spores increase in number and completely fill the host cell cytoplasm, the cell membrane is disrupted and releases the spores to the surroundings.
# These free mature spores can infect new cells thus continuing the cycle.

==Treatment==
[[Fumagillin]] has been used in the treatment.<ref name="pmid18803616"/><ref name="pmid12075057">{{cite journal |author=Molina JM, Tourneur M, Sarfati C, ''et al.'' |title=Fumagillin treatment of intestinal microsporidiosis |journal=N. Engl. J. Med. |volume=346 |issue=25 |pages=1963–9 |year=2002 |month=June |pmid=12075057 |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa012924 |url=http://content.nejm.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=short&pmid=12075057&promo=ONFLNS19}}</ref>

Another agent used is [[albendazole]].<ref name="pmid15954858">{{cite journal |author=Didier ES, Maddry JA, Brindley PJ, Stovall ME, Didier PJ |title=Therapeutic strategies for human microsporidia infections |journal=Expert Rev Anti Infect Ther |volume=3 |issue=3 |pages=419–34 |year=2005 |month=June |pmid=15954858 |doi=10.1586/14787210.3.3.419 |url=http://www.future-drugs.com/doi/abs/10.1586/14787210.3.3.419?url_ver=Z39.88-2003&rfr_id=ori:rid:crossref.org&rfr_dat=cr_pub%3dncbi.nlm.nih.gov}}</ref>

